        "date": "[REDACTED]",
        "content": [
          {
            "attachment": {
              "contentType": "text/plain",
              "data": "DISCHARGE SUMMARY:\n\nPatient Name: [REDACTED]\nAge: 49\nSex: Male\nDate of Admission: [REDACTED]\nDate of Discharge: [REDACTED]\n\nHospital Course:\nThe patient was admitted with longstanding back and left leg pain that was resistant to pain management. He suffered a fall with a left wrist fracture and developed shortness of breath, which led to an emergency room visit. He was diagnosed with two right retroperitoneal masses, which were confirmed to be a benign nerve sheath tumor. A genetic evaluation revealed a large contiguous deletion of chromosome 9p21.3, extending beyond the cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitor 2A (CDKN2A) gene and spanning approximately 25 genes. The patient had a family history of multiple melanomas and other malignancies and was monitored for three years, during which the retroperitoneal masses remained stable. However, he developed progressive back and radicular abdominal pain, and the right prevertebral and right paraspinal lesions continued to grow. Given the patient’s condition and predisposition to malignancy, he was referred to interventional radiology for image-guided RFA. Six weeks after the procedure, there was a decrease in the size of the right prevertebral and right paraspinal lesions. The patient reported an improvement in pain and no longer required methadone for pain control. Follow-up imaging four years later showed stable regression of the anterior prevertebral lesion and further decrease in the size of the posterior paraspinal lesion.\n\nDiagnosis/Conditions:\n-Longstanding back and left leg pain\n-Left wrist fracture\n-Shortness of breath\n-Two right retroperitoneal masses\n-Benign nerve sheath tumor\n-Contiguous deletion of chromosome 9p21.3 extending beyond the CDKN2A gene\n-Multiple melanomas and other malignancies\n-High HgA1C (11.0)\n-Neuropathy\n-Renal insufficiency\n-Two prior cerebral vascular accidents (CVA)\n-Mild residual left hemiparesis\n-Peripheral vascular disease involving iliac stenting\n-Tobacco abuse\n-Obesity\n\nTreatment:\n-Percutaneous biopsy of the retroperitoneal masses\n-Excision of the left sciatic tumor\n-Image-guided RFA\n-Methadone for pain control\n\nCondition at Discharge:\nThe patient’s condition has improved since the procedure, and he has reported less pain. Follow-up imaging showed stable regression of the anterior prevertebral lesion and further decrease in the size of the posterior paraspinal lesion.\n\nFollow-up Care:\nThe patient should continue to follow up with his primary care physician and undergo regular imaging to monitor the progression or recurrence of the retroperitoneal masses.\n\nSigned,\n[REDACTED]."
            }
